Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Halve the @ciabatta{2} and lay them, cut-side up, onto a #baking tray{}.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Spread the garlic over the cut sides of the ciabatta. Drizzle over a little @olive oil{} and set aside.

Cut the @medium tomato{2} into 1cm chunks.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced).

Halve the @avocado{1} and remove the stone. Use a #tablespoon{} to scoop the flesh out onto a #cutting board{}, then chop into 2cm chunks.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, lay the @Serrano ham{4%slices} in the pan and fry until crisp, ~{2-3%minutes} each side.

Once crispy, transfer to a #plate{} covered in #kitchen paper{}. Set aside.

Pop the pan back onto medium-high heat with a drizzle more oil if needed.

Once hot, add the onion and fry, stirring occasionally, until golden, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Add the @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{1%tbsp} and half the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml}, then lower the heat and cook until caramelised, ~{1-2%minutes} more, then remove from the heat.

Meanwhile, bake the ciabatta on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{4-5%minutes}.

While the ciabatta bakes, add the @olive oil{1%tbsp} and remaining balsamic to a large #bowl{}.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then mix together well.

Just before serving, add the tomatoes, avocado and @wild rocket{40%g} to the dressing. Toss to coat.

When everything's ready, share the toasted ciabatta halves between your plates.

Spoon over the caramelised onions and top with a handful of salad.

Drain the @mozzarella{1%ball}, then tear it into small pieces and place on top.

Snap the Serrano ham into shards and scatter over the bruschetta. Serve any remaining salad alongside.

Enjoy!